    "instruction": "Load trace.csv (parse timestamp column with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True')). Restrict to trace records for the candidate services list (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice) and also include frontendservice/root entries that show calls to them. For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair present in the file: \n1) Compute global P95 and P5 over the full available series for that pair (do NOT filter by the incident window for threshold calculation). \n2) Filter that pair's rows to the incident window 2024-01-16 06:54:01 UTC through 2024-01-16 07:24:01 UTC (inclusive). Compute window_count. \n3) Within the window, count anomalies_high as number of rows with value >= global P95, and anomalies_low as number of rows with value <= global P5. Also record earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC) among those anomalies or NULL if none. \nReturn a compact table (limit to top 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_count, p95, p5, window_count, anomalies_high, anomalies_low, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Additionally, return a filtered subset (up to 20 rows) of trace rows in the incident window where cmdb_id is currencyservice or trace_name contains \"from_frontendservice\" or \"to_currencyservice\" showing columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value (limit 20)."
